article.headline: Rasheed tops 10,000 points for career
article.linkText: Pistons beat Nuggets, win seventh straight
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Rasheed Wallace has made a good team better in one short month. Wallace scored 20 points and surpassed the 10,000-point mark in his nine-season career to lead the Detroit Pistons past Denver 94-75 Friday night for their seventh straight victory. The Pistons are 20 games over .500, and 11-3 since trading for Wallace on Feb. 19. Wallace said the transition could not have gone more smoothly, but he doesn't think the Pistons have peaked. "Hopefully, it'll get better," he said. "Right now, we're on a little streak, but we've got a lot of games left. When playoff time comes, we'll get that surge of energy and we'll just ride it out." The Pistons have won by an average of 21.9 points during their streak. "Detroit is playing as well as any team in the league right now," Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "Rasheed Wallace has taken a very good team to a new level." Nuggets rookie Carmelo Anthony, who Detroit passed on to draft Darko Milicic with the No. 2 pick, scored 20 points, but had just four points in the second half. "I don't feel like talking right now," Anthony said after the game. Even though the Pistons are among the top teams in the Eastern Conference, some fans still wish they took Anthony instead of Milicic. A few fans held a sign that read: "Sorry Darko We Should've Got Carmelo." The game was such a rout that Milicic played for just the 26th time this season. Moments after checking in with 3:28 left, he made a low-post shot. Milicic finished with two points, two rebounds and a steal. Detroit's Richard Hamilton scored 20 and Ben Wallace had 10 points, nine rebounds and four blocks. Pistons reserves Mehmet Okur scored 15 points and Corliss Williamson added 11. Denver's Nene had 13 points and 10 rebounds, Voshon Lenard scored 12 points and Andre Miller added 11. The Pistons were behind twice by a point in the first quarter, but didn't trail again. The Nuggets went on a 12-1 run to pull within two late in the third quarter before Detroit's defense and balanced scoring put them away. Detroit's 13-1 burst early in the fourth gave it a 83-68 lead. "We wore them down," Ben Wallace said. "In the fourth quarter, it really started to show. When we play like that, we're always going to be tough to beat." Former Detroit guard Jon Barry, who signed with Denver in the offseason, said the Pistons have the NBA's best defense and are the top team in their conference. "They are the favorites in the East, better than both Indiana and (New) Jersey," Barry said. The Pistons have won seven straight against Denver, which barely fared better than it did earlier this month against them. Detroit won at Denver 97-66 while Anthony missed 13 of 16 shots and scored just eight points.

Game notes
A Guinness Book of World Records mark for "Most People Wearing Wigs -- Single Venue" was surpassed when 6,213 wigs were worn at The Palace. The previous record of 5,574 was set in 2003 during a rugby match in Australia. The total must be registered with Guinness for it to be official. ... Milicic said there's a "99-percent chance" he will be part of Serbia-Montenegro's team in the Athens Olympics. Pistons president of basketball operations Joe Dumars said Milicic might be able to play for Detroit's summer league team and participate in the Olympics. ... Bob Seger, a regular at Pistons games, was given a standing ovation for being inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame on Monday.
